  <div class="views-field-title">
                <span class="field-content"><a href="../blog-posts/china-ready-climate-change">Is China ready for climate change?</a></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-image-fid">
                <span class="field-content"><img src="../files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/Yunnan's&#32;record&#32;drought&#32;has&#32;turned&#32;its&#32;Black&#32;Dragon&#32;Lake&#32;to&#32;be&#32;a&#32;play&#32;yard&#32;for&#32;children.jpg" alt="" title="" width="162" height="120" class="imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default"/></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-library-file-fid">
                <div class="field-content"></div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p>Once again, China‚Äôs ability to handle a changing climate is being tested.</p>

<p>In 2013, rainfall in south China‚Äôs Yunnan province <a href="http://www.eenews.net/public/climatewire/2013/4/16/1">dropped</a> 70 percent below average levels.  This, combined with similar rainfall decline over the past three years, has turned the once water-abundant region into a much drier place.</p>

<p>China is among the countries <a href="http://www.sdpc.gov.cn/zjgx/t20121122_515107.htm">most vulnerable</a> to climate change. An extreme weather event like Yunnan‚Äôs years-long drought is just one of many problems it faces.</p></div>
