  <div class="views-field-field-library-file-fid">
                <div class="field-content"></div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p>As provided for in last month‚Äôs <a href="http://unfccc.int/resource/docs/2009/cop15/eng/l07.pdf">Copenhagen Accord</a>,  China has now submitted its ‚Äúmitigation actions‚Äù (click <a href="../library/chinas-submission-mitigation-actions-copenhagen-accord">HERE</a> to see the text of the letter in our ChinaFAQs Library).  While there was much speculation as to which actions China would submit, in the end China has reported the full set of measures first announced by <a href="../blog-posts/president-hus-un-speech-key-signal-chinese-domestic-policy-will-be-more-carbon-focused">President Hu Jintao</a> at the United Nations in November 2009, and then amplified by the <a href="../blog-posts/chinas-state-council-unveils-40-45-carbon-intensity-target">State Council decision</a> on the 40-45% carbon intensity target at the end of November.</p></div>
