  <div class="views-row views-row-151 views-row-odd">
      
  <div class="views-field-title">
                <span class="field-content"><a href="../blog-posts/chinas-carbon-intensity-target-be-adopted-law">China‚Äôs Carbon Intensity Target to be Adopted into Law</a></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-image-fid">
                <span class="field-content"><img src="../files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/tsinghua.jpg" alt="" title="" width="128" height="120" class="imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default"/></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-library-file-fid">
                <div class="field-content"></div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p>Senior Chinese climate statesman He Jiankun, speaking at the Chinese Pavilion at the Copenhagen Climate Talks, announced that the Chinese carbon intensity would be introduced as legislation to be passed by China‚Äôs National People‚Äôs Congress, its highest law-making body.</p>

<p>Professor He, the Director of Tsinghua University‚Äôs Low Carbon Energy Laboratory and the University‚Äôs former Executive Vice President, spoke December 9 as part of a series of regular talks the Chinese are sponsoring in their first ever dedicated space at a major climate meeting.</p>

<p>Professor He emphasized that China‚Äôs commitment to making the 40-45% reduction in carbon intensity between 2005 and 2020 will be binding domestically, and that the government would also focus on implementing specific programs to meet it.  He argued a carbon intensity goal is the best way to measure progress on climate change mitigation for a country in the midst of rapid industrialization and urbanization.</p></div>
  </div>
  </div>
  <div class="views-row views-row-152 views-row-even">
      
  <div class="views-field-title">
                <span class="field-content"><a href="../blog-posts/chinas-1000-enterprise-energy-conservation-program-beats-target">China‚Äôs 1000 Enterprise Energy Conservation Program Beats Target</a></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-image-fid">
                <span class="field-content"></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-library-file-fid">
                <div class="field-content"></div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p>Covering fully one-third of primary energy use in China, the 1000 Enterprise Program set the goal of reducing energy consumption by 100 million tons coal equivalent by the end of 2010.  In November, China‚Äôs National Development and Reform Commission (NDRC) <a href="http://www.sdpc.gov.cn/zcfb/zcfbgg/2009gg/t20091124_315017.htm">announced that the program had exceeded that goal two years early</a> ‚Äì by the end of 2008, the program had saved 106 million tons coal equivalent, resulting in avoiding 265 million metric tons of CO2 emissions.</p></div>
  </div>
